  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Shelter Repair for shock-affected households in Zabul Province</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project aims to provide further support to 250 shock-affected households in Zabul province (Mizana, Qalat, Shajoy and Tarnak-wa-Jaldak districts) who were severely affected by harsh winter conditions which caused severe shelter damage. Following multi-sector assistance already provided, shelter repair support will be proposed through a flexible cash modality that will allow beneficiary choice but also ensure quality shelter inputs that allow for shelters to be built back better to prevent future damages from similar climactic conditions. Zabul has been selected for two reasons: 1) The province is affected by conflict since several years. On the other hand, the recent shock has added to the sufferings of affected households who are living in desperate conditions. 2) Some of the target locations are hard to reach, where no or less humanitarian support has been provided. Following the shock, the humanitarian agencies were recently granted access to providing life-saving support. DRC would like to build upon this and extend the much-needed shelter support to the affected population.
Target beneficiaries and 250 shock affected households (1750 individuals) who are recently affected by heavy rain and snow and as of start of technical shelter assessment were not able to rehabilitate their shelters

This project will be treated as a pilot, as such standard cluster packages have not been used. Being treated as a pilot project, the approach will be adapted to the situation that develops on the ground. Learnings from this project will inform future cluster packages and responses. learning from this adopted tailored cash for shelter repair approach, will be shared with ES/NFIs based on which can be used by cluster and its partners to inform packages, responses, approaches and standards.</narrative>
  </description>
